segments.text: Testing 1, 2, 3.
Testing 1, 2, 3.
Today is what, April the 8th?
April the 8th.
1979, and we're here to talk about the Texas A&M University Press.
What I'd like to talk about first, though, is John Lindsay, and ask you to tell me a little bit about your childhood, where you were born, how you happened to become an Aggie, and all that stuff.
I mean, incidentally, have you been interviewed formally like this for A&M at all?
Yes, I have.
Mary Ellen Bowers did.
She's got a film now on film on some of these things.
Anyway, let's do it again.
Tell me a little about your childhood.
Where were you born?
Actually, I was born in Waxahachie, Texas.
My father was born and raised in Illinois and came down here during World War I and met a mother who lived in Waxahachie.
I didn't live there but about one year of my life, however, so I don't remember it all.
We moved to Houston when I was about one year old, so I've really called myself a native Houstonian.
There you are.
My father graduated from Wesleyan University in Middletown, Connecticut.
My mother was a music major at Columbia, so they had no connection with any universities
in this part of the world.
But I had a lot of friends at high school at Lamar and a lot of them went to NM during the reign of John Kimbrough, the football team.
So that really swayed me a lot at NM because I had a lot of friends that went there the year before I did.
They came by my house and
Their parents were friends of my parents, and so that's how I got to steward the Texas A&M.
Let's get a little on the hard data.
When were you born?
What's your birthday?
My birthday is July the 28th, 1922.
And when did you arrive at Texas A&M?
In 1940, in the fall of 1940.
And what were you planning to do when you got there?
I had no idea what I was going to do.
I'm still trying to figure out what I'm going to do.
No, I started out in engineering because I really didn't know what to do.
Excuse me.
That didn't last very long, and I switched to a major in economics and a minor in accounting and statistics, which is now the business field, I guess you could say.
That was in liberal arts, I made it with the family.
Good work, liberal arts, right.
That's correct.
finished A&M, or did you get called into service?
Well, I got called into service, right.
We went year-round to school, you know, so in the summer of 43, we got called into Fort Sam Houston.
They picked up the class of 44 and 45 one night, late at night.
We got on the train and went to San Antonio.
And from there, we
I went to the various... No, we did not get our degrees.
I was 14 hours short.
Some did, a class of 43 did.
But 44 and 45 did not.
And we went to, all of us went to Fort Sam, Houston.
And then we sort of spread out from there.
They sent us to, the engineers went to engineering school, OCS rather, and the infantry went to the infantry .
And I was in the field artillery, so I went to Fort Sill at the moment.
And got a, graduated from OCS, second lieutenant, and stayed at Fort Sill.
for about a year and a half and then went overseas to Italy.
Did you do training?
Yes, basic training.
And so then you went overseas in 45?
January of 45.
Europe, France?
Italy.
Italy.
Yeah.
Going to combat?
Well, no.
I was at a replacement.
They didn't need any field artillery officers.
I was a field artillery officer, and there were several of us, and they didn't need any field artillery officers.
And we were in this replacement training center waiting to be called up by somebody.
And while I was there, I was just there for six months, and while I was there, the war was over.
So we got on the ship at Lake Horn, Italy, and went...
through the Panama Canal to Manila in the Philippines.
Oh, did you?
Oh, they just picked you up.
Yep.
We went straight across.
Forty-five days on the ocean liner.
You won't forget that.
No, I won't forget that.
I will not forget that.
That was quite a trip.
I'll bet that was.
Then in the Philippines, I was there when the atomic bomb was dropped on Japan.
We rejoiced, of course, and I still am rejoicing about that.
It saved my life.
No question about it.
And then after that, we left the Philippines and went to Japan, and I spent a year in the Army of Occupation in Japan.
In Tokyo?
In Tokyo.
By that side of Tokyo.
About 20 miles north of Tokyo.
Yeah, it's a beautiful, beautiful place.
I haven't been back.
I know I should.
So far away.
Yeah.
We went to talk to some of the rice farmers.
Yeah.
They were trying to keep American rice out.
Sure.
I don't know what the process was, why I was there, but it was really interesting.
I think they were trying to open the door just to crime or something, which they had.
It's a beautiful, beautiful country.
Boy, it's a mixture of evil and violence.
Right.
Excuse me.
That's all right.
So then you're in Japan for about a year.
Right.
Came home in July of 49.
six after spending 18 months overseas and got married and entered A&M in the fall.
Graduated in January of 47.
Now, when you came back, you didn't go back and record pedestrians.
No.
No, they didn't.
We had a veterans group.
Yeah, that was a tough time.
Right.
That's correct.
This was a tough time for NM.
Boy, NM didn't know what it was in those days.
We had the Board of Regents, I think, was still holding on to their all-military, but they didn't know what to do with the veterans that wanted to come back.
But they, we were separate from the Corps.
There were a lot of us, many veterans as it were, in those days.
Did you, you were married while you were back?
Yes, we were married.
Lived in Park Hall.
My wife, my wife became an Aggie during those days.
She went to school in the east, so she didn't go to school in Texas either.
So it was really nice for her to get that experience.
She really loved it.
She liked midnight jail practices and going with the girls to shop.
It was fun.
So after graduation, where did you go?
Well, I came back to Houston.
And my father was in the insurance business.
There again, I didn't know what I wanted to do, but he talked me into coming to interview with the company that he worked for.
Who was that?
I did.
And I did, and went to work there.
And he and I worked in the same area.
for five or six years, and then we decided to form the Lindsay Insurance Agency, which we did in 1954.
And we've been in that business ever since.
You're being mechanical.
Yes.
My father lived for a long time.
He died when he was 90.
So, you know, he still came to the office a lot during that time.
My brother has an agency in Shreveport.
Oh, he does?
Yeah.
Casualty.
They did pretty good up there, in fact.
You know, they had some really bad years.
Right.
Right.
Well, we've certainly enjoyed our business, and it's been a great hour of changing.
It's the kind of business that you can spend as much time as you want to on it, and then you have time for other things, too.
Of course, in my lifetime, I need a lot of time free, and I'm a long way from it.
When did you get re-involved with Texas A&M?
Right off the bat.
It was an interesting thing.
I had heard from a friend of mine that they had every money at the Rice Hotel, and my office was in the Sterling Building, which is right down the street about two blocks from Rice.
So my first Monday that I was at work, I went to the Rice Hotel for lunch.
And the president of the, I didn't know a soul in the room, the president of the NM Club was asking people if anybody had gone to Milby High School and somebody held up their hand.

Just when I walked in, I didn't know what they were talking about, and they said, well, we've got so-and-so and so-and-so plays football at Milby, and the coach wants somebody, one of the alumni, to go by and see this guy.
And did you do it?
Oh, yeah, I'll do it.
Then he said, does anybody here from Lamar High School?
Nobody held that kind of hand.
So there you are.
And that's where I got started.
Boy, howdy.
I had a tiger by the tail on the first one, too.
It was Robert Smith, who was a handbag in high school.

i stayed with him i'm telling you how sarah my wife stayed married to me because like this thing but he was he was very highly recruited by everybody and uh won't go into all those details but it was a really a tough situation when he ended up losing he went to two lanes and when he got to two lane he didn't like it over there so he called me and said that uh
Did I come over and help him lead Tulane?
So anyway, we got him out of Tulane and back here.
And got him up to A&M.
And he was an All-American halfback.
He was a great football player.
So it was very, very satisfying.
So what year was that?
I was trying to think.
Tulane had some good teams in the 1940s and 50s.
Yeah, they sure did.
They sure did.
This was in 40.
And Bob Smith went on to, actually, it was midterm of 48 when he got to A&M, I think, because he went to Tulane and went on to...
to go to graduate from Lamar, and then went to Tulane, and then at mid-term, I think it was mid-term that we picked him up at Andrew again.
So, 49 and 50 was one of his big years.
Then he went on to play for the Detroit Lions, professional football.
Well, I know Aggies, I guess, pretty well, but why were you so fascinated with continuing your A&M activities?
I don't know.
I don't know.
I just have no idea.
Most Aggies don't.
No, I know.
A lot of them don't.
But I don't know why.
I don't know why.
I did, though, and I liked the school, and I liked all my friends up there, and it was just a fun thing to do.
And it still has been for you, obviously.
And it still has been, still is.
It still is.
I can't help but be interested in almost everything that happens up there.
Let's jump to the press.
Would you first begin to get an idea or hear about an A&M Press or get involved with Warren Law, maybe which came first?
It was Buck Shewitz and I were good friends and I liked his work and the course and he and I had become real close.
And he told me one day, he said, I've got a friend at the University of Texas that you need to know, that you all really like each other.
His name is Frank Wardlaw.
And I said, well, Buck, you know, I don't go to the University of Texas very often.
I don't know that I'll ever meet him, but if he ever comes here, well, I'd like to meet him.
Well, he kept saying, you need to come over to the press and talk to him.
And Buck had gone over to Austin and visited the press, and he knew all those people that Frank dealt with and some of the authors that were over there.
And Frank was trying to get a book done on Buck's fuels.
Oh, even before he came over?
Right.
Oh, yeah.
And I didn't really know that at the time.
But finally one day, um, Buck called me from Austin, and he said that they were having a party at the UT Press for, um, well, and they just walked, just walked out here.
Who was the great, Dobie?
Okay, Bessie.
Is it Bessie Dobie?
Bertha, Bertha Dobie?
Jay Frank Dobie's wife, widow.
It's Bertha.
I believe it's Bertha Dobie.
Anyway, they were having a party for Bertha Dobie.
She was still living.
And the press was having this event, and he said, John, this is the time for you to come over.
I want you to meet Bertha, I want you to meet Frank Waterball, and I want you to meet all these other people that are over here.
This is a good place of mine, and I want to meet you.
So I reluctantly drove over to Austin.
What year was this?
Oh, I don't know.
It was in the late 60s, I guess.
67 or 68, somewhere in there.
I've just forgotten what year that was.
But anyway, went over there and I had a wonderful time.
And Buck was right.
Frank and I hit it off right from the very beginning.
And I didn't know that Frank was kind of behind Buck pushing me to come over there.
And I found out later why he was trying to get me over there.
Because he knew, Frank Warlock knew that I had influence with Buck.
And he, and finally he just got me in this, obviously he said, John, I'm going to lay it on the table.
I want to do a book on Buck Sheebert's art.
And I can't get him, I can't nail him down, but I think you can.
He said.
Right.
I would like for you to do this book and to get some pictures, get the pictures of us, and I'm going to let you run with it.
You do pick the ones, you pick the pictures, you pick the author, you do the whole thing.
And I would not get in the way.
If you do that for me, it would be a wonderful, it would just be a wonderful thing for everybody.
And I, of course, I've never done anything like that before.
But I agreed to do it.
And so that took about a year and a half or two years to research that and get those pictures out.
And so we did a book at the UT Press.
And it has my name all over it.
I mean, it's picked by John Lindsay.
And the only book by Shewitz that was done by the UT Press.
It was fun, though.
But in doing the book, I took pictures of people, of my friends that had them.
Poured the picture, told them I just have it, and gave it back to them.
And it happened to be near Thanksgiving.
And they relate, which I didn't realize was possible, and it was possible.
And the pictures were kept over Thanksgiving.
And I remember one of the Victor friends who had her out-of-town guest coming, and they had that sheet which was over the mantel.
And they didn't have a picture of that over the mantel.
No, they chewed me out for that.
I got, oh, they were furious that they couldn't get the picture done.
Anyway, I got some very good experience in book publishing.
at UT Press.
Let me ask you now, do you consider yourself a book person?
No.
No, I'm not.
Yeah, I didn't think you were.
No, I'm not.
I'm not a book person at all.
But I know the value of books, though.
And I do realize that there are a lot of book people, a lot of book people.
And I do know that...
Well, I didn't know if you had some secret love affair with books.
No, I don't.
It wasn't that at all.
This was for the Pugsheewitz thing.
And I really wasn't thinking about, at that particular time, I don't know that I really thought about the press at A&M, but I really was just kind of
getting used to what a press was, what a university press was.
It wasn't the same as some of the big, big press across the country, the commercial presses.
But we got that book done, and we laughed and celebrated about that.
And Frank and I were, Frank was very appreciative of it.
He took, he got us
Took us hunting.
My sons, I have two boys, and he took us hunting.
We went to one of his authors.
I can't think of anybody's name right now.
Who did Old Yellow?
The book, and it was later a movie, Old Yellow.
Oh, I should know it too.
Anyway, we went to his house.
And my boys just loved it.
They had the best time hunting with Frank.
And then Frank liked baseball.
Bird?
Deer?
Deer.
Deer.
Uh-huh.
And Frank, there's a funny story on that trip.
Frank liked to hunt in the tree.
And he would climb up the tree and took one of my boys with him.
And they were up in the tree, and Frank told this story himself.
And my son, they were up there in the choir and everybody was singing, and my son was between them.
What are you doing?
He said, we're waiting for a dinner.
And so my son said, well, what is that?
My son was about six or seven, I think.
This deer had walked up, Frank didn't even see him.
Anyway, that was a funny experience.
But we had become, then Frank and I had become friends, too.
And he liked baseball, as I said, and when the Astros played, I invited Frank to come down and he brought some of his friends down.
Gibson, I believe, was the author of Gibson.
But one time, I have a house in Galveston, a beach house.
And Frank likes to go anywhere in Texas, wherever it was.
He loves Texas.
He loves to go to the hill country or on the beach or wherever.
So I told him that I'd like to get Rosemary to use my beach house.
So I don't remember what year that was, but he came to my house in Houston and spent the night.
And we were just visiting the night before, we went out to dinner, nothing special.
And at breakfast, right after breakfast, we had finished breakfast.
We were sitting, all sitting there.
I was getting ready to go down to my office.
And Frank was complaining about his board at the University of Texas.
Again, he had done this before.
But he started on it again, about how the board of regents, or the president of the university at the time,
had appointed his press board, advisory board, and they were all Eastern professors.
None of them cared about Texana at all.
They wanted to do early Swahili, or East Africa, or some way off, very scholarly thing.
Which Frank was interested in, but he was more interested in Texana than anything else.
And he wanted to have a mix.
They did it.
And he kept saying, you know, well, I just, just out of the blue, I said, well, Frank, why don't you jump on them?
Why don't you get a bit of all those people?
And we'll make a happy life for you at A&M.
And you know, Rosemary looked up.
He looked up.
And they, just like they had the stabbed in the back or something, I don't know, but they never said a word.
Never said, no, that's not a good idea, hell no, or anything.
They never said anything.
And so I said, well, I'm leaving, I've got to go.
So I walked out and came downtown.
And the first thing I got from my telephone, I called Jack Woodlands.
And I said, Jack, I've got Frank Warlow at my house in Houston.
He's on the way to my beach house in Galveston.
And I have just asked him to come to Texas A&M.
And I think we need a press there.
And Jack said, how much does it cost?
That was his first question.
How much does it cost?
I said, I have no idea what the cost is.
But he said, I said, I think we need to look into it and see what it costs.
So Jack had a lot on his mind at this particular time.
I don't know what all it was, but he had a bunch on his mind.
He said, John, I'll tell you what I'll do.
If you give me three members of the Board of Regents to say, okay, I will look into it.
So, I talked to three or four members, and I told them my situation was wrong.
And they all said, well, how much does it cost?
And I said, well, I don't know how much it costs.
I said, what we want to do, well, we're not committing for anything.
All we want to do is to look into what the cost is and see
Yeah, well, Fort Albritton was one of them.
And Guy King, Waco, and the chairman for 18 years, Clyde Wells.
And fortunately Clyde had just become, just started collecting rare books.
He was interested in books.
And so he, he was, he was most interested.
He said, well Tom, sounds like a good idea.
Let's, let's do look into that.
And I said, well if you don't mind, Clyde, I'll just call Jack and tell him that you were in favor of looking into it.
And he said, that'll be fine.
So I called Jack back, and it was about three hours later.
I called him back, and I said, Jack, you got another job.
I got three members, and here they are, and they're all interested in finding out how much it costs.
So he looked into it, and it wasn't really all that expensive to get a press started.
He was getting kind of enthusiastic about it.
But he had never met Frank Wardler.
And he'd heard of him.
He knew who he was.
Everybody knew who Frank Warhol was.
But he said, well, how are we going to get to, I want to meet Frank.
And I said, well, let me call him and see.
Well, no, I'm jumping ahead of the game.
Frank called me about three days later from my house in Galveston during the cocktail hour.
That's what he said, iced tea.
It was not iced tea.
He was drinking some jellies and all that.
He had had two or three and was feeling no pain at all.
He said, John, he said, you may not remember this, but he said, you remember the breakfast table the other day you suggested?
that I leave the University of Texas at the end of the year, and he said, I thought that was, I didn't say anything, but I thought that was the craziest thing I'd ever heard of.
I just couldn't think of it.
But he said, I've been thinking about it down here.
I've talked to Rosemary about it, and you may be surprised to know that I am, I'm interested in talking about it.
So I said, fine.
I said, we are way ahead of you.
He said, I've already got you in place.
And we're ready to go.
And he said, well, I think that it's got possibilities.
And he said, we'll get together.
We'll talk about it some more when I get back to Austin.
I never did see him over this thing at this time.
But then I got the board members to say okay and Jack said we're ready to go and how do we get together with Frank.
So I called Frank and said look, Jack wants to meet you.
How would you suggest it?
Do you want to come over to College Station?
Do you want to come over to Austin?
I said Jack has to be in Austin.
a lot in business.
So we could come over there sometime and I could drive over there and the three of us could meet.
He said, that sounds like a deal.
And he picked a motel, the Vagabond Motel.
It was kind of a questionable place, but he said
He didn't want to be seen with us.
That's good.
That was kind of the words he used, and I don't want Jack Williams and I to be seen together somewhere.
He said, I've still got a job over here, and I want to make sure that we don't make any waves.
So we met at the coffee shop of the Vagabond Hotel.
And Jack and I, I drove up to the car station, picked up Jack, picked him up, and we met Frank for the first time.
They hit it off real well.
And we were rolling.
And it really was...
There was just nothing in the road to hinder this movement.
I mean the road was wide open.
And Jack cooperated totally.
The Board of Regents cooperated totally.
Frank got everything he asked for, whatever he wanted, he got.
And they were all enthusiastic.
That meant he wanted to find more.
Somebody hadn't thought of this before.
But nobody had Frank Wardlow before.
This guy was, you know, a real new marooner.
And was just a real catch.
I guess anybody really would be proud to have Frank on campus.
Was there any steam, any direction in this direction within the former Students Association per se, through the virus?
No.
They all liked Buck Shewitz.
Sure.
Buck came over, and Buck was great, and Buck and Frank were close friends.
So it was easy.
Whoever was a friend of Buck was a friend of Eric Buck.
Now, what about the A&M Centennial History paper?
Did that enter into it in any way at this time, or were you even aware that it was being developed?
No.
No, it didn't have anything to do with this.
Okay.
It didn't have anything to do with this.
I'll tell you another interesting thing, Tony.
The first time Frank came to College Station, he stayed, Frank stayed at the Holiday Inn in town.
And Buck was there.
Shewitz was there.
He was at the old Regent's quarters.
Remember those visitor rooms downstairs?
Buck was staying there.
So I drove up and I took Rosemary and Frank out to dinner, just the five of us.
And I had Rosemary and Frank in my car and I drove up to the side of the old Regent's Quarters and Frank looked out the window and he said, what is this?
And I said, this is the old Board of Regents house.
It's kind of not in really too good shape.
The Board of Regents wasn't using it.
It was really not good.
But she had a place, a free place to stay.
And that's where he was using the bedroom downstairs.
Well, I got out of the car and went in, got Buck, and we were coming out the door.
And when I came out of the door, Frank and Rosemary had gotten out of my car and had walked all the way around the front of this house and around the back.
And he hardly spoke to Buck.
I mean, he said hello, I guess, but he said, listen, I want to know about this house.
What's it used for now?
And I said, well, it's not used for anything.
I think we're going to probably tear it down.
Oh, he said, no, you can't tear this house down.
He said, this is where I want the press.
I mean, he said that.
He said, this is where I want the press.
And I said, well, gosh, Mike, I had no idea that what kind of a building a press wanted anyway.
I never thought of it that he'd want this kind of a building.
But when he, that was the first thing he talked, when he saw Jack the next day, he said, I found a place.
That's amazing.
And that's where it was.
He loved that house.
His letters were just full of that.
He was so happy.
He really was.
And that really did help him cement the relationship with A&M.
Everything just fell into place.
The opportunity was right.
He really was disgruntled about Texas.
In fact, that's the word he used about the faculty earlier.
He said they're disgruntled.
And Spur, I think, was the president.
Yeah, that's right.
That's right.
Now, one of the first things Brian did when he got back in was got back to A&M.
I bet you think it's a good story before that.
Yeah.
He's organized this advisory committee.
Right, right, right.
And you are probably a bit ahead of that.
I wasn't.
I wasn't ahead of it.
I was long ahead of it, yeah.
Okay.
Now, what was its approach?
Was it primarily money raising?
Well, money raising, yeah.
Okay.
Yeah.
He told me about how he got these, he would get people and they would sponsor a series.
Sponsor a series and then he would go back into it.
And I introduced him to, I guess, all the people that did the series.
Ken Montague.
I introduced him to Joe Moore, too.
They have a place in Hawaii.
Frank had an art series he wanted to do and I had the money and I had done it.
But I didn't at that time and I'm pretty well committed.
You know he made more than the R3.
Pugh?
Well, he came from the DuPont.
DuPont introduced it to Pugh.
Okay.
And Pugh didn't want his name involved.
Right.
That's correct.
That's correct.
That's correct.
He didn't want other people getting DuPont.
That's probably what he wanted.
He just didn't want everybody soliciting.
Yeah, now with these, were you personally involved?
Oh, yeah.
He was a good friend of mine.
I said, look, I want to take you to lunch.
I want you to meet Frank Wardlaw.
We want to talk about books.
And he said, you know, and Frank was, I mean, that kid was one.
Where was Montague?
Was he in Houston?
Houston, yeah.
Okay.
He was in Houston.
And he came, and I'm sure he had no idea of ever doing anything like that either, and neither did I.
But he came up and we did it.
That's another thing that Wardolph mentioned in his letters quite a lot, you know,
Aggies, former students, really believe this is their press.
That's correct.
That's correct.
They bought books.
He was enchanted with that.
Right.
They were interested and they bought books.
But a press, college press, is really a hard sell.
Yes, it is.
It is.
Faculty don't really appreciate it.
I don't think adequately.
I think you're right.
I think you're right.
I think we're better known outside the...
outside of our own place and we are in the place yeah and i think some of the letters frank's letters are the reflex of this uh-huh symptoms really of any universal class well that's uh didn't know
a lot of people in Houston.
In fact, they kept Tim Cannon under wraps over there.
Frank was, he really wasn't treated as a first-class citizen.
Oh, we sure did.
And he just loved it.
He reported directly to the President and everything he wanted, he got.
And he couldn't have been happier.
I'm sure he was walking into this world of academia without a degree and all that, and you get the whole complex as he did at Texas later.
They just changed their world beautifully.
But that's what makes Frank Wardlaw a great man.
He became Dwight and Aggie.
He really did.
He was a great publisher.
So the series, now the...
The Centennial Series money, I know, got dumped back into the press.
Were you involved in that decision at all?
No.
I don't think of the decision to publish it, or... Well, no, I mean funding the money.
No.
